hacienda patrons seeking status as New World feudal magnates; "rings" of greedy territorial politicians on the make; women finding their own way in a man's world; Anglo homesteaders looking for a place to settle in the American West; and Dutch investors in search of gargantuan returns on their capital. The European and American newcomers all "mistranslated" the prior property regimes into new rules, to their own advantage and the disadvantage of those who had lived on the land before them. Their efforts to control the Maxwell Land Grant by wrapping it in their own particular myths of law and custom inevitably led to conflict and even violence as cultures and legal regimes clashed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLand tenurezNew MexicoxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  aamerican west.  achicano.  acolonialism.  acolorado.  aethnicity.  afrontier.  ahistory.  ahomestead act.  aindigenous people.  aindigenous rights.  aland development.  aland grant.  aland rights.  alegal history.  alucien maxwell.  amexican americans.  amexican governors.  amexican history.  amexico.  anative american.  anew mexico.  apioneers.  arace.  asettler colonialism.  asettlers.  asettling the west.  asouthwest.  asquatters.  asupreme court.  atreaties.  atreaty of guadalupe hidalgo.  aus courts.  awild west.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022744640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092648640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520926486423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520926486/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 20